{"title_page": "Minuteman Bikeway", "text_new": "[[File:Minuteman Bikeway with old tracks.agr.jpg|thumb|300px|right|The Minuteman Commuter Bikeway in Lexington, with abandoned tracks from former use as a rail line]]\n{{Minuteman Bikeway}}\nThe '''Minuteman Bikeway''' is a 10-mile (16-kilometre)<ref>Some sources list it erroneously as 11 miles.  The confusion arises because the mile marker at the beginning of the trail in Bedford is 1 instead of 0.  Wikipedia editors have measured the distance as shown on maps and in Google Earth, and it appears to be 10 miles to within a few hundredths of a mile. For further verification, see: [http://www.pps.org/great_public_spaces/one?public_place_id=18 Project for Public Spaces] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060719234246/http://www.pps.org/great_public_spaces/one?public_place_id=18 |date=2006-07-19 }} or [http://www.bedforddepot.org/history/index.html About the Lexington Branch]</ref> paved multi-use [[rail trail]] located in the [[Greater Boston]] area of [[Massachusetts]]. It runs from [[Bedford, Massachusetts|Bedford]] to [[Alewife (MBTA station)|Alewife station]], at the northern end of the [[Red Line (MBTA)|Red Line]] in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], passing through the towns of [[Lexington, Massachusetts|Lexington]] and [[Arlington, Massachusetts|Arlington]] along the way. Also along the route are several notable regional sites, including [[Alewife Brook Reservation]], [[Spy Pond]], \"[[Arlington\u2019s Great Meadows]]\" (actually located in Lexington), [[Lexington Battle Green|the Battle Green in Lexington]], and [[Hanscom Air Force Base]].\n\nAt its Cambridge terminus, the bikeway connects with four other bike paths: \n*the [[Fitchburg Cutoff Path]] \n*the [[Cambridge Linear Park]] which, in turn, leads to the [[Somerville Community Path]]. \n*the Alewife Brook Greenway, a connection to the [[Mystic River]] bike path, following [[Alewife Brook]].<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Town of Arlington, MA |url=http://www.arlingtonma.gov/public_documents/ArlingtonMA_DPW/projects/greenway/index |title=Alewife Brook Greenway Corridor Improvement Project |date=July 11, 2012 |accessdate=2013-08-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120721162544/http://www.arlingtonma.gov/public_documents/ArlingtonMA_DPW/projects/greenway/index |archivedate=July 21, 2012 }}</ref> The Alewife Brook extension received $4M from the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009]] as the \"Minuteman Bikepath Connector\" project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eot.state.ma.us/default.asp?pgid=content/releases/pr021010_ARRA&sid=release|title=Patrick-Murray Administration Obligates 100% of ARRA Highway Funding One Month Ahead of Schedule|date=2010-02-10|accessdate=2010-03-02|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100216235118/http://www.eot.state.ma.us/default.asp?pgid=content%2Freleases%2Fpr021010_ARRA&sid=release|archivedate=2010-02-16}}</ref>\n* a sidewalk path to [[Fresh Pond (Cambridge, Massachusetts)|Fresh Pond Reservation]].\n\nPlans are underway to extend the Somerville Community Path to downtown [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]], which would create a much larger continuous bikeway accessible from the Minuteman.\n\nAt the Bedford end, the Minuteman Bikeway connects with the [[Narrow Gauge Rail Trail]] and the [[Reformatory Branch Rail Trail]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bedforddepot.org/railtrails/index.html|title=Rail-Trails at Bedford Depot Park|website=www.bedforddepot.org}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n[[File:Topographic maps of Arlington, Belmont, Lexington Massachusetts 1946.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Map from 1946, where Boston & Maine Railroad (B&M) passes along the route of today's Minuteman Bikeway]]\n\nThe path comprising the current Minuteman Bikeway has a long history. The trail closely approximates the route that [[Paul Revere]] took on his famous ride in 1775, which heralded the beginning of the American Revolution.\n\nAlong the way to becoming a railroad, the path's [[right-of-way (transportation)|right-of-way]] was laid out east of Lexington in 1846 by the [[Lexington and West Cambridge Railroad]] and west of Lexington in 1873 by the [[Middlesex Central Railroad]].\n\n[[Railbanking]] of the line was first proposed in 1974, three years before passenger rail service was discontinued, and a full seven years before rail service was discontinued altogether (in 1981). In 1991, the final plan for the conversion was approved, and construction started on the original section of the bikeway. The path was dedicated in 1992 and completed the following year.<ref name=\"viser2007\"/>\n\nIn 1998 the bikeway was extended from East Arlington to Alewife station (in Cambridge). In 2002 it was repaved in Arlington and in 2004 the Bedford Depot Park Enhancement Project was completed at its western terminus.<ref name=\"viser2007\">Viser, Matt (2007), \"Rage on the bikeway\", The Boston Globe, Volume 272, Number 1, 2007-07-01, p.A1.</ref>\n\nIn 2008, the bikeway was the fifth inductee into the national Rail-Trail Hall of Fame by the Rails-to-Trails Conservancy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minutemanbikeway.org/Pages/HallofFame.html|title=Bikeway-Hall of Fame|website=www.minutemanbikeway.org}}</ref>\n\nThe property is currently owned by the [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]] and leased to the municipalities through which it passes on an interim basis.{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}} The MBTA at one point planned to use this right-of-way to extend the [[Red Line (MBTA)|Red Line]] to Arlington Center and Arlington Heights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boston.curbed.com/archives/2014/02/the-red-line-stops-in-arlington-and-lexington.php|title=The Red Line Stops in Arlington and Lexington|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nBeginning in Spring 2015, the crossing of the path through Arlington Center is expected to be rebuilt to be less discontinuous.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arlingtonma.gov/home/showdocument?id=22444|title=Project Update: September 25, 2014|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[http://www.arlingtonma.gov/home/showdocument?id=2932 Map of Preferred Alternative] - Arlington Center Safe Travel Project, March 21, 2013</ref>\n\n==Uses==\nArea residents use the bikeway for a host of activities, including [[cycling|bicycling]], walking, [[jogging]], and [[inline skates|inline skating]]. The main use of the path, however, is for casual biking.<ref name=\"viser2007\"/> In the winter there is often enough snow on the bikeway for [[cross-country skiing]].  However, it is now plowed from Alewife Station to Bedford.<ref name=\"gilsdorf\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2008/06/29/popular_bike_trail_gets_even_better/?page=2|title=Popular bike trail gets even better|last=Gilsdorf |first=Ethan|date=June 29, 2008|publisher=boston.com|accessdate=2009-06-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2010/01/24/on_minuteman_bikeway_in_winter_beginning_to_see_their_way_clear/|title=On winter\u2019s path, seeing their way clear|first=Brock|last=Parker|date=24 January 2010|publisher=|via=The Boston Globe}}</ref> No motorized vehicles are allowed except for powered [[wheelchair]]s and emergency vehicles.\n\n==Future possibilities==\n\nNew connections under contemplation include one from Lexington to the Battle Road Trail and one to the [[Charles River]] bike path via Fresh Pond Reservation and the abandoned [[Watertown Branch Railroad]]. A portion of the latter path, at the Watertown end, has been completed and design work on the remaining section to Cambridge is expected to be finished in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mass.gov/eea/docs/dcr/news/public-meetings/materials/projects/2015-11-30-watertown-cambridge-presentation-c.pdf |title=Data|website=www.mass.gov|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, state officials announced that the Somerville Community Path would be extended alongside the [[Green Line Extension]], creating a continuous 4.5 mile route from the Minuteman Bikeway to Boston\u2019s [[Charles River Bike Path]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Conway|first=Abby Elizabeth|title=Somerville Bike Path To Extend To Boston|url=http://www.wbur.org/2014/04/30/somerville-bike-path-extension|accessdate=3 May 2014|newspaper=WBUR|date=30 April 2014}}</ref> Officials had contemplated abandoning the path portion of the GLX in order to save costs, but after hiring new management, a contractor agreed to the parallel path while still cutting costs.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n==Gallery of views along the bikeway==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"140px\">\nBedford Depot Park.jpg|Bedford Depot Park, with old B&M [[Budd Rail Diesel Car|RDC]]\nMinuteman Bikeway in Bedford, August 2007.jpg|In Bedford, near Wiggins Avenue\nFile:Minuteman Bikeway at the Lexington Depot, MA.jpg|Lexington Depot\nFile:Spy pond arlington massachusetts 050322.jpg|Spy Pond, Arlington\nFile:Snow minuteman bike path arlington massachusetts 050322.jpg|Snow on the path, Arlington\nFile:Minuteman Bikeway, Cambridge.jpg|In Cambridge, near [[Alewife (MBTA station)|Alewife station]] and the junction with the [[Fitchburg Cutoff Path]]\nFile:AlewifeBikeParking.agr.2001.JPG|Bike parking at Alewife station\nFile:Trail connector along Alewife Station Access Road, February 2010.jpg|Connector to [[Cambridge Linear Park]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Minutemen]]\n*[[Uncle Sam Memorial Statue]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.minutemanbikeway.org/ Minuteman Bikeway - official website]\n*[http://www.traillink.com/ViewTrail.aspx?AcctID=6015981 Minuteman Commuter Bikeway] | Rails-to-Trails Conservancy\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gJT5jHMQ420&list=PLTOf_IkJHwrgEgU8y_Q4YFX74FqvBh_88 Video | Virtual cycling video of the Minuteman Bikeway] (2012)\n*[https://vimeo.com/322717980 Video | \"The Minuteman Trail, America\u2019s 500th Rail\"] (1993)\n*[http://www.folb.net/ Friends of Lexington Bikeways]\n*[